80","1180":"1180","1206":"1206","1216":"1216","1324":"1324","1159":"1159","1225":"1225","1268":"1268","Abt 1210":"about 1210","1188":"1188","1210":"1210","1155":"1155","after 1188":"after 1188","about 1155":"about 1155","1219":"1219","Stockpool,, Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Stackpole, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Stackpole, Pembrokeshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Stackpole","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Welsh: habitational name from Stackpole (Pembrokeshire), apparently named with Old Norse <i>stakkr</i> ‘stack’ + <i>pollr</i> ‘pool’, referring to a stack of rocks on the coast at the entrance to Broadhaven. The name was taken to Ireland and adapted by settlers of Norman descent, where it is recorded in Dublin as early as 1200. The name has been Gaelicized as <b>de Stacapúl</b>; the family was also known in Irish as <b>Galldubh</b> ‘dark stranger’."],"variants":[{"name":"Stackpoole","meanings":["English (Cheshire) and Welsh: variant of   Stackpole  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has 